TCP..> Transmission Control Protocol
UDP..> User Datagram Protocol


| Feature        | TCP                       | UDP                    |
| -------------- | ------------------------- | ---------------------- |
| Connection     | Connection-oriented       | Connectionless         |
| Speed          | Slower (reliable)         | Faster (no overhead)   |
| Reliability    | Guaranteed delivery       | No guarantee           |
| Error Checking | Yes, extensive            | Minimal                |
| Ordering       | Maintains packet order    | No ordering            |
| Use Case       | Web, Email, File Transfer | Gaming, Streaming, DNS |

Key Differences:

TCP = Reliable, ordered, connection-based

UDP = Fast, connectionless, best-effort

TCP = Web/File Transfer
UDP = Gaming/Streaming/DNS


* Common TCP Flags

TCP flags control the state and behavior of communication.

SYN
Initiates a new connection (synchronization)

ACK
Acknowledges receipt of data or packets

FIN
Gracefully closes a connection

RST
Forces an immediate connection reset

PSH
Pushes data immediately without buffering

URG
Marks data as urgent and high priority

Note:
Used in Nmap scans, port scanning, firewall evasion, and TCP manipulation attacks.
